1 _OID cc2f62f9-09e5-49ca-a998-91e5103f81ef
1 DATE Sept 1993
1 PLAC London
1 _DSCR Trial of william gouldstone
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>  &amp;lt;iframe src=&amp;quot;http://res.levexis.com/clientfiles/default/4/ancestry.htm&amp;quot; style=&amp;quot;border:0px none ; width: 0px; height: 0px;&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/iframe&amp;gt;   &lt;!-- SN:TREESUI1
2 CONC 5 --&gt; &lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p style="margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span&gt;Reference Number: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span&gt;t18
2 CONC 830910-849&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p style="margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&
2 CONC lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;849. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;WILLIAM GOULDSTONE (26) was indicted for, and charge
2 CONC d on the Coroner&amp;#39;s Inquisition with, the wilful murder of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;Charles Gouldstone. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt
2 CONC ;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;MESSRS. POLAND &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;and &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;MONTAGU WILLIAMS &lt;/span&g
2 CONC t;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Prosecuted&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt;; &lt;span&gt;MESSRS. GRAIN &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;and &lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt;ELLIOTT &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Defended.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&
2 CONC gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;ADA&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt; HAMILTON &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&g
2 CONC t;&lt;span&gt;. I am the wife of William Hamilton, and am a monthly nurse; we live at Walthamstow&amp;mdash;I knew the prisoner and his wife and three children; they had lived at Walthamstow at the house where this matter occurred, occupying two ki
2 CONC tchens and one back room, for about eleven months&amp;mdash;I had lived there about ten weeks up to that time, occupying the front room on the same floor, with my husband&amp;mdash;their three children were, &lt;span style="background: red"&gt;Char
2 CONC les, about 3 1/2 years old; Herbert, 2 1/2 years; and Frederick, 16 months&lt;/span&gt;&amp;mdash;the prisoner was a whitesmith by trade, I believe, and used to go every day to his work in London&amp;mdash;on 1st August I attended his wife in her c
2 CONC onfinement; she was delivered of &lt;span style="background: red"&gt;two male children&lt;/span&gt;&amp;mdash;up to that time the prisoner attended regularly to his work&amp;mdash;the confinement took place on Wednesday, at 10.30 at night&amp;mdash
2 CONC ;he went to his work on the Thursday and Friday, but not after the Friday&amp;mdash;on two occasions before the following Wednesday, the 8th, I noticed him very strange and quiet, and sitting crying&amp;mdash;I only saw him once the worse for drink
2 CONC ; that was on the Friday after the babies were born, after he came home&amp;mdash;up to that time he had always been a sober, industrious man&amp;mdash;on Wednesday, the 8th, I was in the bedroom attending to the prisoner&amp;#39;s wife and the bab
2 CONC ies; he came home about a quarter past 5 in the evening, and went into the bedroom; I went into the kitchen, where the two eldest children were playing; the third child, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;Frederick,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/
2 CONC strong&gt; was in the bedroom with the wife and babies&amp;mdash;the prisoner came into the kitchen; I said &amp;quot;I wondered who it was; you did frighten me&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;that was about a quarter past 5; he made no answer; his usual tim
2 CONC e for coming homo was 7.30&amp;mdash;I, did not say anything else&amp;mdash;I went back into the bedroom and left him with the two children in the kitchen&amp;mdash;he was there three or four minutes, not longer, and then came into the bedroom&amp;
2 CONC mdash;his wife said &amp;quot;What makes you home so early?&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he said he came out while the manager was gone to dinner&amp;mdash;she said &amp;quot;Did you tell them I was confined?&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;No&amp;quo
2 CONC t;&amp;mdash;she said &amp;quot;Didn&amp;#39;t you tell Mr. Graves?&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he is the foreman at the works&amp;mdash;the prisoner said &amp;quot;No,&amp;quot; and then took little Frederick up off the bed and went out into the kitchen
2 CONC , which is on the same floor, with him&amp;mdash;I did not notice anything in his manner or demeanour at that time; he seemed very quiet&amp;mdash;I went on washing the babies, and when I had washed one I went into the kitchen to fetch something&am
2 CONC p;mdash;the prisoner was sitting on the fire-guard, which comes all round the grate and rests on the floor; the fire was alight; the prisoner&amp;#39;s back was towards it; the children were playing about there&amp;mdash;the prisoner had a piece o
2 CONC f string or thin twine in his hand; I did not say anything to him, and went back again into the bedroom&amp;mdash;I was away from the kitchen for about ten minutes, and then returned and asked him if he had had his tea&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;N
2 CONC o&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;I said his tea was ready then; it was on the table and the tea was on the hob&amp;mdash;the three children were then playing in the kitchen&amp;mdash;I went through the wash-house to the other kitchen on the same floor&amp;mda
2 CONC sh;the prisoner was still sitting on the fire-guard, and I noticed the perambulator was moved from under-neath the cistern, and a chair, which usually stood by the side of the cistern, placed there&amp;mdash;to reach the cistern you had to get o
2 CONC n a chair&amp;mdash;I asked the prisoner who placed the chair there; Charley said &amp;quot;My &lt;em&gt;dada&lt;/em&gt; put it there&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;I went back again into the bedroom, got the prisoners wife out of bed, remade the bed, and wa
2 CONC s there some little time&amp;mdash;I might have been there twenty minutes before I saw the prisoner again; then he came along the passage and looked into the room; I told him he could come in; he said something to himself, I could not distinguish t
2 CONC he words, and went into the kitchen again&amp;mdash;I thought he wanted to say something to his wife, and so I spoke to her and left the bedroom and went downstairs&amp;mdash;the kitchens are on the first floor&amp;mdash;when I was on the stairs go
2 CONC ing down I heard the kitchen door open and I heard the prisoner go into the bedroom&amp;mdash;I had got to the yard door when I heard screams of &amp;quot;Murder&amp;quot; from the prisoner&amp;#39;s wife; that could not have been more than two o
2 CONC r three minutes after I had left her&amp;mdash;I rushed at once up to the bedroom door and tried it and found it locked&amp;mdash;the prisoner&amp;#39;s wife said &amp;quot;Come in; he is murdering my children&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;I could not forc
2 CONC e the door; I called for help; Mrs. Clark was at the bootom of the garden; she came, and we both tried to force the door, but could not&amp;mdash;I called to the prisoner to open the door, but I never heard him answer&amp;mdash;after we had been a
2 CONC t the door about three minutes he opened it&amp;mdash;I said &amp;quot;Mr. Gouldstone, what have you done, you wicked man?&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;No, I am a happy man&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;I passed into the bedroom to his wife, and h
2 CONC e passed me and went out into the kitchen&amp;mdash;he did not say anything about the other children&amp;mdash;I then went up to the bedside and saw the babies; they were both alive, bleeding from the mouth and nose, and appeared to be dying, serio
2 CONC usly injured&amp;mdash;I took a small sheet and covered them over, so that the mother should not see them, and sent for a doctor&amp;mdash;then from what the wife said I went into the kitchen&amp;mdash;the prisoner was there with the youngest of th
2 CONC e three elder children in his arms, wringing wet and apparently dead; he laid him on the floor, and then I turned round and saw the wife coming into the kitchen, and I went back with her and remained with her in the bedroom about a quarter of an ho
2 CONC ur I dare say, and then went out again into the kitchen and saw the three, Charles, Herbert, and Frederick, lying there on the floor side by side, all wet and dead&amp;mdash;the prisoner was standing there&amp;mdash;I went back to the bedroom and r
2 CONC emained there some time till the policeman brought the prisoner into the bedroom&amp;mdash;he said to his wife &amp;quot;All your children are dead, and I shall be hanged, and you will be single again; you wished they were dead, and now you have go
2 CONC t your wish&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he had not said anything as to how they had come by their death&amp;mdash;he then kissed his wife&amp;mdash;she asked him if he had any money&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;Yes,&amp;quot; and put his hand in his pocke
2 CONC t and gave her 3&lt;em&gt;s&lt;/em&gt;. 4&lt;em&gt;d&lt;/em&gt;., and then he was taken away by the constable&amp;mdash;I remained behind&amp;mdash;previous to that one of the constables asked me for the hammer, and I afterwards picked up from th
2 CONC e floor by the dressing-table and near the bed an ordinary large hammer for knocking in nails, and gave it to the constable&amp;mdash;I had never seen the hammer before&amp;mdash;I attended to the mother and the two babies; one died half an hour af
2 CONC terwards in my arms, and the other at 2 o&amp;#39;clock the next morning.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&l
2 CONC t;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; When I first went into the kitchen the children were sitting on the floor playing, and the prisoner was sitting with his back to the fire looking down at his hands, not at them
2 CONC &amp;mdash;both his hands were holding the twine; he was turning it round and looking at it&amp;mdash;when I came back on the second occasion he was still looking at the twine and playing with it&amp;mdash;the room was a small one&amp;mdash;the chi
2 CONC ldren seemed happy&amp;mdash;when I left the wife, before I went up and found the door locked, I left the two babies in bed; she was sitting up&amp;mdash;since I have known them I have had opportunity of observing his demeanour towards his wife an
2 CONC d children&amp;mdash;as far as I can say up to this time he had always appeared a good husband, and very fond of his wife and children, and they seemed very happy together&amp;mdash;I have seen him play with the children&amp;mdash;on the Sunday h
2 CONC e used to sit in the kitchen and amuse them&amp;mdash;I have seen that several times; I was a good deal in there with them&amp;mdash;after the twins were born I noticed he was very strange; he seemed so quiet, and used to sit still, and if you spok
2 CONC e to him he did not answer you; he seemed absent, and far less cheerful than he had done before&amp;mdash;I have heard his wife say he had come home with a headache that came on suddenly&amp;mdash;I have seen him put his hand to his head a great de
2 CONC al, and he would then complain of pain&amp;mdash;I have never heard him complain at all about being short of money, or of not being able to support the children&amp;mdash;as far as I noticed he was always a sober, well-conducted man, and always cam
2 CONC e home every night; never missed since I have known them.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;sp
2 CONC an&gt;EMMA CLARK &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;. I am the wife of Charles Clark, a carpenter, and the tenant of 8, Courtnay Place, St. James&amp;#39;s Street&amp;mdash;the prisoner and his wife and family had lodged with us about eleven mon
2 CONC ths&amp;mdash;they were strangers to me before they came to lodge there&amp;mdash;the prisoner has always been a steady, quiet man, very fond of his wife, and kind to his children&amp;mdash;Mrs. Gouldstone was confined on Wednesday, 1st August, abo
2 CONC ut 10.30 p.m.&amp;mdash;the prisoner was not at home then&amp;mdash;when he came in I told him his wife had been confined, and that there were two&amp;mdash;he looked strange when I told him so&amp;mdash;he did not say anything&amp;mdash;I did no
2 CONC t see him the night after the confinement&amp;mdash;on the Wednesday afternoon, the 8th, about 5.30, I was in the garden hanging out the clothes to dry, when I heard the nurse run upstairs and call for help&amp;mdash;I ran up after her, went to th
2 CONC e bedroom door, and tried to open it&amp;mdash;it was locked on the inside&amp;mdash;I heard the wife say &amp;quot;He has killed my babies&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;the prisoner opened the door, and said &amp;quot; You can come in&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;
2 CONC I went into the bedroom, and saw the two babies on the pillow; they were breathing, and bleeding from their noses and mouths&amp;mdash;Mrs. Hamilton covered them over with a sheet&amp;mdash;I ran downstairs and called for the police, and then wen
2 CONC t back to Mrs. Gouldstone&amp;#39;s bed-room, then followed Mrs. Hamilton into the kitchen, and saw the three little boys, Charles, Herbert, and Frederick, lying on the floor in a row, apparently quite dead&amp;mdash;their clothes and hair were wet
2 CONC &amp;mdash;I saw the prisoner apprehended&amp;mdash;I had not about this time or any time that week seen the prisoner the worse for drink.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&l
2 CONC t;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I was examined before the Coroner, but not before the Magistrate&amp;mdash;I said &amp;quot;I heard Mrs. Goulds
2 CONC tone say &amp;#39;He has killed my babies;&amp;#39; at this instant he opened the bedroom door, and said &amp;#39;You can come in, it is all done&amp;#39;&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;that is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;fon
2 CONC t face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;WILLIAM CHEESEMAN &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;(&lt;em&gt;Policeman N&lt;/em&gt; 86). On the eveni
2 CONC ng of Wednesday, 8th August, I was sent for to 8, Courtney Place, where the prisoner lived&amp;mdash;I went upstairs and saw him in the kitchen&amp;mdash;the three children were lying on the floor there dead, and wet&amp;mdash;the prisoner was stoo
2 CONC ping over them&amp;mdash;his hat and coat were off, and his shirtsleeves were slightly rolled up&amp;mdash;I was in uniform&amp;mdash;when I went in the prisoner said &amp;quot;Good evening, policeman, I have done it now, and I am happy, and read
2 CONC y for the rope&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;I cautioned him that what he said would be used in evidence against him&amp;mdash;he put on his hat and coat, and said &amp;quot;Let me see my wife?&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;I said nothing, and went with him into the b
2 CONC edroom where the wife was&amp;mdash;the wife spoke first&amp;mdash;she said &amp;quot;Oh you wicked man, what have you done?&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;I have killed all your children, now you will be single again, and I shall be hanged&
2 CONC amp;quot;&amp;mdash;his wife said &amp;quot;Have you any money?&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;Yes, a little&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he gave her all he had, a two-shilling piece or half-crown, and a shilling and two penny pieces&amp;mdash;he kis
2 CONC sed his wife and bade her good-bye, and I took him away to the station&amp;mdash;on the way he said &amp;quot;When I took my money last week I thought of buying a revolver to do it with, but I altered my mind, because I thought it would make too mu
2 CONC ch noise. I had a hard job with the two biggest, but the other little b&amp;mdash;, I soon settled him; I thought it was getting too hot to have five b kids in about three years and a half&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;I made a note three or four minutes aft
2 CONC erwards; I have got it with me&amp;mdash;he added &amp;quot;Now I am happy, I thought it was time to put a stop to it&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;at the station he said &amp;quot;I have done it like a man&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he was charged with the murde
2 CONC r of the three children, and attempting to murder the two babies&amp;mdash;the charge was read over to him by the inspector&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;Quite right, sir&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he was put in the cells after that&amp;mdash;it was about 2
2 CONC 5 minutes altogether from the time I first went into the kitchen to the time he was put into the cell&amp;mdash;during all that time he appeared sober&amp;mdash;I noticed nothing in his manner or demeanour&amp;mdash;he appeared to understand wha
2 CONC t I said to him and what he said to me.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined
2 CONC .&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; It was about 20 minutes to 6 when I took him into custody at the house&amp;mdash;when he kissed his with just before he went away he simply said &amp;quot;Good-bye&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;she was on the bed, and h
2 CONC e leant over the foot of the bed and kissed her&amp;mdash;when he was leaning over the three children and when I took him into custody he seemed excited.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt
2 CONC ;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;GEORGE FOLKARD &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;(&lt;em&gt;Police Inspector N&lt;/em&gt;). I was at the police-station on the Wednesday ev
2 CONC ening when the prisoner was brought there in custody by Cheeseman. Cheeseman said &amp;quot;This is a charge of murder, sir; this man is charged with murdering his five children&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;the prisoner said &amp;quot;That is right, sir
2 CONC , I did it; now I am happy; I did it like a man, too&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;I then left him in custody at the station, and went to the house with Dr. Gould&amp;mdash;I returned to the station about half-past 7 and charged him with murdering his thre
2 CONC e children, Charles, Herbert, and Frederick, and attempting to murder his two male infants&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;Quite right, sir; what condition is the &lt;em&gt;missis&lt;/em&gt; in? I suppose some of you gentlemen have been round?&amp;quot
2 CONC ; Dr. Gould replied &amp;quot;Tolerable&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;the prisoner said &amp;quot;Are the two young ones dead?&amp;quot; I said &amp;quot;No&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;about 8 o&amp;#39;clock he was put into a cell&amp;mdash;up to that time he appea
2 CONC red sober&amp;mdash;I could not see the appearance of drink&amp;mdash;I thought he appeared slightly excited when he was first brought in, that was all&amp;mdash;he appeared to understand what he said and what I said to him&amp;mdash;I saw him agai
2 CONC n at 8.30 next morning&amp;mdash;in the meantime the other two children had died&amp;mdash;I then charged him with the murder of the five&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;Yes, sir, the other two are dead, then?&amp;quot; I said &amp;quot;Yes&amp;quot;&a
2 CONC mp;mdash;I examined the cistern in the kitchen&amp;mdash;the top of the cistern is about six feet from the floor and about 10 inches from the ceiling&amp;mdash;there was about 14 inches of water in it&amp;mdash;that was the same night.&lt;/span&gt;
2 CONC &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; The cistern i
2 CONC s long but narrow; it runs the whole length of the room.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;spa
