2 CONC p;mdash;a piece of string was tied round the neck of the eldest; it was Loose.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&
2 CONC gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;WILLIAM CHEESEMAN &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;(&lt;em&gt;Re-examined&lt;/em&gt;). I took possession of this hammer (&lt;em&gt;produced&lt;/em&gt;) at the time&amp;mdash;it is a common hammer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/fo
2 CONC nt&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;The following Witnesses were called for the Defence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&
2 CONC gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&g
2 CONC t;THOMAS GOULDSTONE&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;. I am the prisoner&amp;#39;s father, and live at Great Sampford, in Essex&amp;mdash;my wife, the prisoner&amp;#39;s mother
2 CONC , is alive; she is very bad in her mind now, and has been for a good many years&amp;mdash;she was in a very bad way about 18 years ago; I kept a woman with her&amp;mdash;she tried to &lt;em&gt;grain&lt;/em&gt; herself with a scarf. [&lt;span&gt;A J
2 CONC URYMAN&lt;/span&gt;: Grain is the Essex word for strangle.] I have taken a knife away from her several times during that time&amp;mdash;she was going to make an end of herself, as far as I could see&amp;mdash;about eight weeks ago she threatened t
2 CONC o make away with herself&amp;mdash;she was in a very bad state of mind when the prisoner was born&amp;mdash;my wife has a married sister living in the neighbourhood of the name of Andrews&amp;mdash;she has not been right for two years; she has som
2 CONC e one to look after her to keep her at home&amp;mdash;she has not threatened to take her life that I know of&amp;mdash;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;Charles Gouldstone, a second cousin to the prisoner, died in a madhouse&lt;/span&gt; Know whe
2 CONC ther she died mad or not.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;
2 CONC &lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I have seven children; the eldest is a daughter&amp;mdash;the prisoner is the third&amp;mdash;I believe that they are all right but him&amp;mdash;he went to school, and since he left he has been at work with me, and afterwar
2 CONC ds in employment, always getting his living by his daily labour&amp;mdash;he was five years in this one place&amp;mdash;he was a blacksmith with me&amp;mdash;I saw him last before the 8th of August just after Christmas&amp;mdash;he did not look ver
2 CONC y comfortable&amp;mdash;my wife has not been in any asylum; I keep her at home&amp;mdash;I have not seen anything wrong about my daughter&amp;mdash;my wife is a sober woman&amp;mdash;it was about 18 years ago that she tried to strangle herself; sh
2 CONC e was not taken up for it; I had business troubles about 18 years ago; it was at that time that my wife tried to strangle herself&amp;mdash;it was about 18 years ago she took the knife up&amp;mdash;Mrs. Andrews, my wife&amp;#39;s sister, has neve
2 CONC r been in any asylum; she lives with her husband.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Re-e
2 CONC xamined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; All my other sons are right except the prisoner as far as I know&amp;mdash;when I saw him last I could see he was not quite right, but we did not know what there was to trouble him; that was just after C
2 CONC hristmas, at my place at Stamford Hill&amp;mdash;I was living there then&amp;mdash;he did not do anything then, but he was not very comfortable, so I and my wife thought&amp;mdash;I have had trouble with my wife to keep her from doing herself harm&
2 CONC amp;mdash;the last time I was up with her all night&amp;mdash;sometimes she appears all right, and then suddenly she tries to do herself harm&amp;mdash;it was about two months ago that I sat up in this way, I cannot say to a day.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/f
2 CONC ont&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;ROBERT GOULDSTONE &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&l
2 CONC t;span style="background: red"&gt;. I am the eldest son, and the prisoner&amp;#39;s brother&amp;mdash;I live at Great Sampford with my father&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;mdash;I have lived there with my brother before he came to London&amp;mdash;w
2 CONC hen at Finchingfield he worked with me, and I remember his complaining of his head&amp;mdash;that is about eight years ago&amp;mdash;he suffered from an accident and had a rupture&amp;mdash;when he suffered from rupture pains he suffered more pain
2 CONC s in the head&amp;mdash;he complained a great deal more when the rupture troubled him&amp;mdash;he did not say anything about the pains, he wished himself dead at times; I have heard him say so&amp;mdash;we have always been afraid to bring anythin
2 CONC g up to affect my mother in any way&amp;mdash;she was looked after&amp;mdash;at times she was allowed to go about by herself, not always, because we have been afraid she would do an injury to herself&amp;mdash;we used to have to hide the knives an
2 CONC d razors from her because we were afraid she would make an end of herself&amp;mdash;I have heard her say she would make an end of herself with knives&amp;mdash;I know my aunt, Mrs. Andrews&amp;mdash;they don&amp;#39;t have any one except those in t
2 CONC he house to look after her&amp;mdash;I remember going to see her on a Sunday evening, she sat on all the chairs in the room in the space of a few minutes&amp;mdash;it struck me as peculiar the way she was acting, and I thought she seemed very stran
2 CONC ge in her ways.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt
2 CONC ;&lt;span&gt; I could not say whether it was about seven or eight years ago that the prisoner was ruptured, six or seven years ago I should think&amp;mdash;it was when he was ruptured he had pains in his head&amp;mdash;he did not tell me he was kep
2 CONC t awake at night&amp;mdash;he was a blacksmith at this time&amp;mdash;that is a very noisy trade, and he had a headache&amp;mdash;it was a good many years ago that he said he wished himself dead.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;
2 CONC font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;EMILY GOULDSTONE &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;
2 CONC . I am the prisoner&amp;#39;s sister&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;, and am in service in London&amp;mdash;I have noticed my mother&amp;#39;s conduct for many years past, it has been through trouble in business&amp;mdash;she has attempted to commit suici
2 CONC de several times&amp;mdash;I have myself heard her threaten to do it.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em
2 CONC &gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I heard her threaten to do so about a fortnight or three weeks ago&amp;mdash;I have not seen my brother very often, we are a long way apart&amp;mdash;I saw him last about two month
2 CONC s ago&amp;mdash;I was at my sister&amp;#39;s&amp;mdash;I knew he had been for five years at this firm in Thames Street, working there regularly every day and going home to his wife and children at Walthamstow.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
2 CONC &lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Re-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I have heard of my mother attempting suicid
2 CONC e before a fortnight ago, years ago.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;WILLIAM GRAVE
2 CONC S &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;. I am foreman of the department in which the prisoner worked at the Falkirk Ironworks, Upper Thames Street&amp;mdash;I have Known the prisoner ever since he was born&amp;mdash;he came to the works about fiv
2 CONC e years ago, and married some four or five months afterwards&amp;mdash;they lived with me for about the first three years after their marriage, and the three elder children were born in my house&amp;mdash;they seemed to live like all other workin
2 CONC g people, happily together&amp;mdash;I never saw any cause to complain&amp;mdash;he always seemed fond of his children&amp;mdash;he had many peculiar little ways, but being foreman I did not mix up with the men only so far as my duty compelled me&a
2 CONC mp;mdash;I did not myself notice anything particular till the 2nd of August&amp;mdash;I then noticed something peculiar, and went from my end of the shop to where he worked and said to him, &amp;quot;William, are you well, or have you got the tooth
2 CONC ache?&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he was rubbing his head and face&amp;mdash;I asked him whether there was anything the matter with him&amp;mdash;he said &amp;quot;No, only my head is very queer&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;it is my practice if any man is ill or an
2 CONC ything is wrong to persuade him to go home for a few hours, and I was going to do the same with the prisoner&amp;mdash;on Friday I gave him a job to do in the regular way, and I found he was regularly confused with the work I gave him, and I compla
2 CONC ined to him he did not get on so well as he had at other times; and he made no reply&amp;mdash;he left on that Friday night&amp;mdash;it was our beanfeast on Saturday, the next day; then there was Sunday and the Bank Holiday, when we did not work&a
2 CONC mp;mdash;he ought to have been there on the Tuesday; he was not, nor on the Wednesday&amp;mdash;I did not know anything about his wife&amp;#39;s confinement at the time, but I particularly noticed on the next day after she was confined, the 2nd o
2 CONC f August there was something wrong in the man.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-e
2 CONC xamined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; When he first came to work for this firm he was a blacksmith; we then made him a whitesmith&amp;mdash;he earned 25&lt;em&gt;s&lt;/em&gt;. a week&amp;mdash;on the Friday night before this occurred I had p
2 CONC aid him his wages and made him a present of 10&lt;em&gt;s&lt;/em&gt;., according to the custom of the firm&amp;mdash;he always thanked me for that&amp;mdash;that was on Friday, 3rd, about 5 o&amp;#39;clock&amp;mdash;I went to my own beanfeast; he w
2 CONC ent where he thought proper, as everybody else did; I cannot tell if he went to a beanfeast&amp;mdash;he did not say he had got twins on the Thursday when I thought he was ill&amp;mdash;I did not know if he had been kept up all night owing to his w
2 CONC ife&amp;#39;s confinement and had got headache.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;CHAR
2 CONC LES CAKEBREAD &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;. I work at the Falkirk Ironworks&amp;mdash;I worked there with the prisoner for some years as his mate&amp;mdash;he has frequently said that he would throw himself in front of a train if he thoug
2 CONC ht he could kill himself instantaneously&amp;mdash;I could not give any date for his saying that&amp;mdash;he said he would throw himself down the lift-hole if he thought he would kill himself right out without lingering afterwards&amp;mdash;I trie
2 CONC d to pass it off as a joke; I never thought he meant anything serious in it&amp;mdash;he did not make a joke of it, he spoke seriously&amp;mdash;I believe he was rather popular with the workmen, and was a very quiet, peaceable man&amp;mdash;he ha
2 CONC s been very despondent at times, and I have asked him if I could do anything for him, he has complained of pains in his head and asked me if I would knock his brains out with a hammer&amp;mdash;that I treated as a joke and took no more notice of.&l
2 CONC t;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I c
2 CONC annot give any date when that occurred: it was about six months ago, while we were at work&amp;mdash;ho seemed to have a determination as if he meant it as a reality&amp;mdash;I cannot say but he had plenty of opportunity; I was working with him a
2 CONC t the lift&amp;mdash;it was quite recently that he talked about the train&amp;mdash;he has always attended to his work regularly and earned his wages.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt
2 CONC ;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;BENNETT GOULDSTONE &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;. I am employed at the Falkirk Ironworks, an
2 CONC d am the prisoner&amp;#39;s brother&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;mdash;about four months ago he said to me that he should like to throw himself down the lift hole&amp;mdash;he was suffering very much from rupture&amp;mdash;he said he should like t
2 CONC o kill himself out of his misery&amp;mdash;he complained of pain about his head, and rupture at the time&amp;mdash;he used to wander about as if something were wrong in him, and be very strange.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;f
2 CONC ont face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; He did his work regularly&amp;mdash;he suffered very mu
2 CONC ch from rupture, and was very low spirited about it, it pained him at times&amp;mdash;I do not know where he was on the Saturday, the day of the beanfeast; or on the Monday, Tuesday, or Wednesday; he was not at work&amp;mdash;he did not tell me whe
2 CONC re he had been.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;JOHN CLARK &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt
2 CONC ;&lt;span&gt;. I am also employed at the Falkirk Ironworks&amp;mdash;I have heard the prisoner on many occasions wish that he were dead, and also that he wished some one would hit him on the head and kill him out of the way&amp;mdash;I don&amp;#39;
2 CONC t know what caused him to say so, but he did say so&amp;mdash;during the time he was in my company, as far as I can say, he was speaking solemnly and seriously; he was not laughing at all over it&amp;mdash;I heard him complain of suffering from a r
2 CONC upture, and from pains in his head, nothing further.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;C
2 CONC ross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; He complained a great many times about rupture, and Was very low spirited at times, and he could seldom cough without he doubled himself up to do so&amp;mdash;it was not on those occasions he sai
2 CONC d he wished himself dead; he has said so on frequent occasions afterwards.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&
2 CONC lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Re-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I have heard him say he wished he was dead, and ask to be struck on the dead when fie was not complaining of any pain.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font fa
2 CONC ce="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;GEORGE SKELTON &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;. I am also a workman in the shop with the prisoner at Fal
2 CONC kirk Ironworks&amp;mdash;some months ago the lift rope broke; the lift did not fall&amp;mdash;I was with the prisoner in the lift at the time; it was on the second floor&amp;mdash;I said &amp;quot;You had better jump out&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;we jump
2 CONC ed out and I said to the prisoner &amp;quot;Get a bit of string, we will tie it down to the old iron&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he says&amp;quot; Never mind, it goes to the bottom; it will only kill me out of the way&amp;quot;&amp;mdash;he said it very se
2 CONC riously&amp;mdash;the only time I heard him say anything of the sort before or after was one morning some months before this affair&amp;mdash;I met him and he seemed very much depressed coming to work&amp;mdash;he did not say anything coming along
2 CONC , but as soon as he got in the shop he seemed different&amp;mdash;he was dancing and singing foolish things, what they cull the Salvation Army hymns.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;
2 CONC /font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; He was low-spirited, and then when he got to work among the workmen he began to be joyous&amp;mdash;
2 CONC he was sometimes low and sometimes high-spirited&amp;mdash;the lift broke seven or eight months ago&amp;mdash;I have sometimes seen the men do reckless things, not often, at our place&amp;mdash;he did not go down in the lift; I stopped him&amp;mdas
2 CONC h;I advised him not to do it, sad remonstrated with him.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&
2 CONC gt;Re-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I told him to come out.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;
2 CONC &lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;WILLIAM HENRY WESTBROOK &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;. I am manager at the Falkirk Ironworks&amp;mdash;during the time prisoner was with me he was a very quiet, steady man&amp;mdash;I never noticed that he incline
2 CONC d to be foolhardy in the works or on the lift, or anything of that sort&amp;mdash;I never heard that he played any practical jokes; they are kept from me&amp;mdash;he was a quiet man, almost bordering on moroseness&amp;mdash;he would go home by him
2 CONC self and come by himself, and never seemed to have a companion with him.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt
2 CONC ;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; He was a very fair worker&amp;mdash;the work did not require much intelligence; it is mere fitting up, work which has been fitted before.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&
2 CONC lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;HOWARD JOHN KINNAIRD &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;. I am one of the partners of th
2 CONC ese ironworks&amp;mdash;I have seen the prisoner there&amp;mdash;I have not noticed anything about him; I have heard he was a very steady workman&amp;mdash;we have fully 1,000 workmen&amp;mdash;he has been a steady man as far as I know&amp;mdash;th
2 CONC e whole feeling of his fellow-workmen is that he is certainly insane.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;sp
2 CONC an&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;CHARLES GOULDSTONE (&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style="background: yellow"&gt;charles F goldstone?)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong
2 CONC &gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style="background: yellow"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style="background: yellow"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"
2 CONC &gt;I live at Epping, and am first cousin to the prisoner&amp;#39;s father&amp;mdash;he had a son named William, who had been a soldier, and who, about 21st April, 1880, was taken to the Brentford Lunatic Asylum and confined there till about Octobe
2 CONC r, 1881, about 16 months&amp;mdash;he died there in confinement&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;fo
2 CONC nt face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; He had been in the Army&amp;mdash;he had never been abroad further than Ireland&amp;mdash;he was subject to fits&amp;mdash;I think sometimes the
2 CONC y were only drink; I never saw anything particular in them&amp;mdash;he drank occasionally; he was not a drunkard.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"
2 CONC &gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;JOHN BYFORD &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;. I am the brother-in-law of the prisoner&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;mdash;he has bee
2 CONC n in the habit of visiting me&amp;mdash;I married his sister&amp;mdash;he would usually call on Saturday afternoon and sit in a chair and play with his hat&amp;mdash;if I spoke to him he would invariably answer me the wrong question and take thre
2 CONC e or four minutes to answer me, and I would frequently remark that I thought he was very strange in his manner.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt
2 CONC ;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I should think I last saw him before this occurred, a fortnight before Bank Holiday&amp;mdash;I don&amp;#39;t know where he was a few day
2 CONC s before this occurred.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;WILLIAM SUNDERLAND &lt;/span
2 CONC &gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;, M.D. I practise at Thaxted, in Essex&amp;mdash;&lt;span style="background: red"&gt;I know the prisoner&amp;#39;s mother and also her sister, Mrs. Andrews&lt;/span&gt;&amp;mdash;I have attended the prisoner&amp;#39;s m
2 CONC other, and in my opinion she is in an unsound state of mind&amp;mdash;I have attended her at intervals during the last eight years&amp;mdash;during the whole of that time despondency was the particular form of her unsoundness of mind&amp;mdash;I ca
2 CONC nnot say how long she has been in that state&amp;mdash;the fits of despondency came at intervals, then ceased, and came on again&amp;mdash;she has not attempted to commit suicide to my knowledge&amp;mdash;the sister is not of sound mind&amp;mdash;
2 CONC I have attended her professionally&amp;mdash;she is suffering from the same form of insanity, despondency&amp;mdash;her husband is a small farmer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/fo
2 CONC nt&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; The prisoner&amp;#39;s mother has not been certified nor been confined as a lunatic; she is living at h
2 CONC ome with her husband, and the sister, Mrs. Andrews, lives at home. with, her husband, and a grown-up daughter is kept to look after her&amp;mdash;I do not know the cause of despondency of the prisoner&amp;#39;s mother or of Mrs. Andrews.&lt;/span&g
2 CONC t;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Re-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; She is now cont
2 CONC inually restless and thinks her husband will fail in business, and thinks they will be turned out into the streets, and it makes him move about from place to place.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" siz
2 CONC e="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;GEORGE HENRY SAVAGE &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;, M.D. I am physician at Bethlehem Hospital&amp;mdash;I have examined the pri
2 CONC soner, and from the examination alone I should consider him rather weak in mind, as evidenced by a slowness of appreciation of questions concerning the crime of which he is accused; when speaking about it he seemed not to appreciate in any way th
2 CONC e gravity of the charge&amp;mdash;beyond that from my personal examination I can say nothing&amp;mdash;I have heard the evidence as to his being a steady workman, quiet, and fond of his wife and children, and the details of the killing of the child
2 CONC ren&amp;mdash;from that I should think his mind was unsound at the time he &amp;#39;committed the act&amp;mdash;such symptoms as have been deeailed by his fellow-workmen are frequently present with persons of unsound mind&amp;mdash;I suppose they a
2 CONC re to be found in persons of Bound mind, but certainly not as a rule&amp;mdash;I have heard the evidence as to his mother and aunt; the insanity on the mother&amp;#39;s side having been proved, I should say the prisoner has a very great tendency t
2 CONC o become insane, and if insanity, however remote, were proved on the male side, it would considerably increase the liability in the offspring.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&g
2 CONC t;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Cross-examined.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt; I saw the prisoner yesterday for not more than a quarter or half an hour; I was called to see him by his so
2 CONC licitor, and knew I was to examine him as to the state of his mind, and that he was to be tried for murder; that was the only time I saw him&amp;mdash;I cannot say if at that time he thoroughly understood he was to be tried for murder&amp;mdash;I s
2 CONC poke about the gravity of his crime, that he had killed live children, but nothing about the trial&amp;mdash;speaking alone from the conversation I had with him, and what I saw of him, I had no reason to doubt that he was a man of sound mind; o
2 CONC r I might say rather to prove that he was a man of unsound mind; it was compatible with sanity or insanity&amp;mdash;from what I saw of him on Saturday I would not certify him as a lunatic; I would say that he was not suffering from any active for
2 CONC m of mental disease; I could not say he was a lunatic; he did appreciate questions, although rather slowly&amp;mdash;his conversation with me was that of a rational man&amp;mdash;I should say he knew that the penalty for murder was death, but if h
2 CONC e knew I do not think it would have influenced his actions&amp;mdash;the opinion I gave that he was of unsound mind at the time he committed the act was formed from sitting in Court and hearing the evidence, and having seen him as well&amp;mdash;
2 CONC I heard that he said that he had killed the children, and that he should be hanged for it; I judged from that that at the time he knew he was committing a crime for which he was liable to be sentenced to death&amp;mdash;I believe that he knew he wa
2 CONC s killing the children, and that the penalty for that act was death.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;spa
2 CONC n&gt;&lt;span&gt;GUILTY &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;.&amp;mdash;&lt;em&gt;DEATH. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font face="Times New Roman" size="3"&gt;  &lt;/font&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
